      "prompt": "Roll or choose — this is what overran the Aurelia, the slow-burn truth beneath the repair sandbox. Do NOT reveal early; let it surface through logs, the state of the sections, and what [[Halcyon]] does and does not remember. Optional to foreground: a campaign can stay pure restoration, or become the uncovering of this.",
      "options": [
        {
          "id": "still-here",
          "name": "It's Still Here",
          "description": "The horror is dormant, not gone — and the player's repairs are slowly waking it.",
          "detail": "IT'S STILL HERE — The thing that emptied the Aurelia is dormant, not gone: nesting in the cold, the dark, the breached and airless sections, gone quiet because the station went quiet. The player's repairs are the alarm clock. Heat, light, pressure, power, the smell and sound of life returning — each draws it back, and the better the Aurelia gets, the more it stirs. The campaign's central tension becomes: rebuild without ringing the dinner bell — choose what to power and when, wall off what you wake — or rebuild deliberately toward the strength to face it and end it. Progress and danger rise together."
        },
        {
          "id": "the-station-changed",
          "name": "The Aurelia Is Changing",
          "description": "The horror passed through and left the station altered; it is slowly becoming something else.",
          "detail": "THE AURELIA IS CHANGING — Whatever came through is gone, but it left its mark on the station itself, and the Aurelia is slowly becoming something else. Systems behave wrong in ways that aren't simple damage; the fabricators print things that were never in the spec; the geometry of a corridor drifts between visits; the arboretum grows what shouldn't grow. Every repair is a quiet tug-of-war against a transformation that has its own direction. Restoring the Aurelia means deciding, eventually, whether the player is bringing back what it was — or midwifing what it is trying to become, and whether that is a horror or a wonder."
        },
        {
          "id": "the-owners-did-this",
          "name": "The Owners Did This",
          "description": "The horror was the owners' own doing; the quarantine and the convenient inheritance are a burial.",
          "detail": "THE OWNERS DID THIS — The horror was the owners' own doing — a project in the research labs, a thing they made, bought, woke, or fed, that got loose. The quarantine and the tidy bequest of a dead station to an expendable, far-flung relative are not an accident; they are a burial, and the heir is part of the disposal. Someone outside — a board, a cleanup contractor, a watcher on a distant relay — is waiting to confirm the Aurelia stays a tomb, and would prefer the new owner stay in it. The mystery the player uncovers: what the owners were really doing aboard, why the inheritance fell to them, and who is still watching the station go quiet for good."
        }
      ]
    }
